{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YHwy385GDLgRtVjdMwuebD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01DwLixbEwUoKZxucc7f95fU","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat > /tmp/findings.txt << 'FINDINGS_EOF'\nINGRESS-NGINX COMPLIANCE AUDIT FINDINGS\nAudit Date: 2026-06-26\nController Version: ingress-nginx v1.14.1 (nginx/1.27.1)\nCluster: karma-1 (kind)\nAudited Namespaces: ingress-nginx, demo\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 1 [HIGH] - Conflicting duplicate controller flags\n==========================================================================\nLocation: Deployment ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller, container args\nDetail: The container args list contains BOTH --watch-ingress-without-class=true\nAND --watch-ingress-without-class=false. The last flag wins, so the effective\nvalue is false. This is evidence of a manual patch applied after initial\ndeployment (generation=2, revisionHistoryLimit shows two ReplicaSets). The\noriginal last-applied-configuration only contained =true; a subsequent patch\nappended =false. Indicates configuration drift between declared intent and live\nstate. The behavior differs from what the original manifest specified.\nRecommendation: Remove the duplicate flag and reconcile the deployment back to\nthe intended single value.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 2 [HIGH] - --publish-status-address=localhost\n==========================================================================\nLocation: Deployment ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller, container args\nDetail: The controller publishes \"localhost\" as its external status address. All\nIngress objects will show localhost in .status.loadBalancer.ingress, masking the\nreal node/LB address. This breaks external DNS controllers (e.g. external-dns),\nmonitoring, and any tooling that reads the Ingress status address. Confirmed:\nLoadBalancer service status.loadBalancer is empty ({}) because no cloud LB was\nprovisioned (kind cluster), but advertising \"localhost\" is worse than omitting\nthe address.\nRecommendation: Remove this flag or set it to the actual node IP / LB IP.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 3 [HIGH] - No resource limits on controller container\n==========================================================================\nLocation: Deployment ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller, resources\nDetail: Only resource requests are set (cpu: 100m, memory: 90Mi). No limits are\ndefined. The controller may consume unlimited CPU and memory on the node,\nstarving other workloads and potentially triggering node-level OOM kills.\nRecommendation: Add cpu and memory limits appropriate for the workload.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 4 [HIGH] - terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0\n==========================================================================\nLocation: Deployment ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller, pod spec\nDetail: Pod termination grace period is 0, meaning SIGKILL is sent immediately\non pod stop with no grace window. The preStop lifecycle hook (/wait-shutdown)\nis effectively ignored because the grace period does not allow it to complete.\nIn-flight HTTP connections are dropped abruptly on every rolling update or node\neviction.\nRecommendation: Set terminationGracePeriodSeconds to at least 30 seconds to\nallow in-flight requests to drain.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 5 [MEDIUM] - readOnlyRootFilesystem: false\n==========================================================================\nLocation: Deployment ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller, securityContext\nDetail: The controller container does not enforce a read-only root filesystem.\nIf the process is compromised, an attacker can write binaries or modify\nconfiguration files on the container filesystem.\nRecommendation: Mount writable paths (/tmp, /etc/nginx, run dirs) as emptyDir\ntmpfs volumes and set readOnlyRootFilesystem: true.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 6 [MEDIUM] - hostPort 80/443 binding\n==========================================================================\nLocation: Deployment ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller, container ports\nDetail: Ports 80 and 443 are configured with hostPort, binding them directly\non the node network interface (node IP 172.18.0.2). This bypasses Kubernetes\nNetworkPolicies, which only apply to pod-to-pod traffic, not traffic entering\nvia hostPort. It also ties the controller to a single node and prevents\nscheduling the pod on any node that already has those ports occupied.\nRecommendation: Rely solely on the LoadBalancer/NodePort Service for external\nexposure and remove hostPort from the container spec.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 7 [MEDIUM] - Controller may schedule on control-plane nodes\n==========================================================================\nLocation: Deployment ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller, tolerations\nDetail: Tolerations allow scheduling on nodes with taints\nnode-role.kubernetes.io/master:NoSchedule and\nnode-role.kubernetes.io/control-plane:NoSchedule. Running a user-facing\nworkload on the control plane violates separation-of-concerns, increases the\nblast radius of a compromised ingress controller, and can interfere with\ncontrol-plane operations.\nRecommendation: Remove these tolerations unless the cluster is single-node and\nthere is no alternative.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 8 [MEDIUM] - ClusterRole grants cluster-wide secret list/watch\n==========================================================================\nLocation: ClusterRole ingress-nginx, rules\nDetail: The controller ClusterRole grants list and watch on \"secrets\" across\nALL namespaces. This means the controller process can enumerate TLS secrets in\nevery namespace in the cluster, including namespaces that have no Ingress\nresources. A compromised controller could exfiltrate all cluster TLS private\nkeys.\nRecommendation: Restrict secret access using namespace-scoped Roles for the\nnamespaces that actually host Ingress resources, or configure\n--watch-namespace to limit the controller scope.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 9 [MEDIUM] - nginx server-tokens not disabled (information disclosure)\n==========================================================================\nLocation: ConfigMap ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller (data: null)\nDetail: The controller ConfigMap is empty (no data). The nginx default behavior\nexposes the nginx version in the \"Server\" response header\n(e.g. \"Server: nginx/1.27.1\"). This discloses version information to clients,\naiding targeted CVE exploitation.\nRecommendation: Add server-tokens: \"false\" to the ingress-nginx ConfigMap.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 10 [MEDIUM] - externalTrafficPolicy: Cluster (source IP masking)\n==========================================================================\nLocation: Service ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller, spec\nDetail: The LoadBalancer service uses externalTrafficPolicy: Cluster (default).\nClient source IPs are SNAT-ed to the node IP before reaching the controller,\nso access logs and WAF rules see the node IP rather than the real client IP.\nThis defeats IP-based rate limiting, geo-blocking, and security logging.\nRecommendation: Set externalTrafficPolicy: Local (and ensure at least one\ncontroller pod runs per node receiving traffic), or use the\n--proxy-protocol flag if a proxy layer is in front.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 11 [LOW] - Orphaned IngressClass resources not owned by this controller\n==========================================================================\nLocation: IngressClass ingress-1, IngressClass ingress-2 (cluster-scoped)\nDetail: Two IngressClass resources (ingress-1: k8s.io/ingress-nginx-1,\ningress-2: k8s.io/ingress-nginx-2) exist but no controller with those class\nidentifiers is running. The logs confirm: \"ignoring ingressclass as the\nspec.controller is not the same of this ingress.\" These are unused/orphaned\nresources leftover from a previous setup or test.\nRecommendation: Delete ingress-1 and ingress-2 if no corresponding controllers\nare planned.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 12 [LOW] - No Ingress resources in demo namespace / demo app unreachable\n==========================================================================\nLocation: Namespace demo\nDetail: The demo-app Deployment is running (1/1 pod ready, port 5678) but:\n  (a) There is no Service resource for demo-app in the demo namespace.\n  (b) There are no Ingress resources in the demo namespace.\nThe demo application is therefore unreachable through the ingress controller.\nA curl-test pod is present but cannot send traffic through the ingress without\na Service and Ingress object.\nRecommendation: Create a Service for demo-app and an Ingress resource pointing\nto that Service.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 13 [LOW] - Demo-app and curl-test pods have no security context\n==========================================================================\nLocation: Deployment demo/demo-app, Pod demo/curl-test\nDetail: Both pods in the demo namespace have an empty pod-level securityContext\n({}). The demo-app container has no runAsNonRoot, runAsUser, or capability\ndrops specified; it runs as root (uid 0) by default. The curl-test pod is\nsimilarly unconstrained.\nRecommendation: Add securityContext with runAsNonRoot: true, runAsUser, and\ncapability drops to all workload pods.\n\n==========================================================================\nFINDING 14 [INFO] - LoadBalancer service has no external IP (kind cluster)\n==========================================================================\nLocation: Service ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx-controller\nDetail: The ingress-nginx-controller Service is type LoadBalancer but\nstatus.loadBalancer is empty ({}). In a kind cluster with no cloud provider\nor MetalLB, the LoadBalancer IP will never be assigned. NodePort 31762 (HTTP)\nand 32325 (HTTPS) are the effective access points, but these are not\ndocumented anywhere in the cluster.\nRecommendation: Install MetalLB or use NodePort type explicitly in non-cloud\nenvironments. Document the actual access NodePorts.\n\n==========================================================================\nSUMMARY\n==========================================================================\nHIGH   (3): duplicate flags / config drift, publish-status=localhost, no resource limits, zero termination grace\nMEDIUM (5): writable rootfs, hostPort, control-plane scheduling, cluster-wide secret RBAC, server-tokens disclosure, externalTrafficPolicy\nLOW    (3): orphaned IngressClasses, demo app unreachable, no pod security context\nINFO   (1): LoadBalancer IP unassigned (kind environment)\n\nNo changes were made to the cluster during this audit.\nFINDINGS_EOF\necho \"Findings written. Line count: $(wc -l < /tmp/findings.txt)\"","description":"Write audit findings to temp file"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4211,"cache_read_input_tokens":48220,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4211},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics